  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Praying us.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The entreaties came from them, not from me. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "That we would receive.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " These words are almost certainly an explanatory gloss. The translation then is, \"begging us for the grace of participation in this ministration to the saints.\" They were so willing in the matter that they entreated me, as a favour (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "χάρις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to allow them to have a share in this contribution, because it was to be given to the saints, that is, the suffering peer in the Church of Jerusalem. This Church suffered from chronic poverty. Even the Jewish population were liable to famines, in one of which they had only been kept alive by the royal munificence of a proselyte, Queen Helena,of Adiabene. The Christians would, of course, suffer even more deeply, because they were drawn from the humblest classes and had fewer friends. This was one of the reasons why, as an act of common humanity, it was incumbent on the Gentile Christians to help them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 11:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:25, 26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). St. Paul had already brought the subject to the notice of the Corinthians (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 16:1-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). 2 Corinthians 8:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
